What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The listed category of each is assigned a value between 0 and 20. Credit grades are ranked using the Prosper Rating system ('AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'HR').

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in seeing what characteristics make a loan risky and safe.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think BorrowerAPR, Current Delinquencies, Credit score range, and debt to income ratio will help determine the risk level of a loan. I expect that the lower the debt to income ratio is, the safer the loan.

def labels(xlabel, ylabel, title):
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)

debt_to_income_bins = np.arange(0, 3, 0.05)
plt.hist(loans['DebtToIncomeRatio'], bins=debt_to_income_bins)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mtick.PercentFormatter(1.0, decimals=0))
labels('Debt to Income Ratio', 'Count', 'Debt to Income Ratio');

The average debt to income in the dataset is 27%, and the standard deviation is 55%. This graph shows a right skew distribution. I decided to make the maximum x-value 200% to remove outliers. Note that the lower the debt to income ratio, the better. Next, I will look at how many loans are for each credit grade using the prosper rating.

9.311207471647766

Most of the loans have either been paid off or are in the process of being paid off. I did not like the look of the first visualization, so I decided to remove the outliers. 9.3% of the loans have been charged off, meaning the bank considered it a loss.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most loans were for Debt Consolidation and had a right skew distribution. Debt to income ratio showed a right skew. Stated monthly income and Open Revolving Accounts also had a right skew. In the Loan Status bar chart, all loans with past due status, finalpaymentinprogress, and canceled status were tiny. Yes, I performed a transformation on the loan status and debt to income ratio variables.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Loan status had the most unusual distribution. I did the transformations because both variables had many outliers, so removing them would make the chart look better and accurately represent the data.

labels('Current Delinquencies', 'Loan Status', 'Current Delinquencies in each Loan Status');

The error bar I chose for this bar plot is the standard deviation. Defaulted loans have the highest average current delinquencies, with about 2. Loans with Chargedoff and Defaulted status have higher averages and standard deviations than loans with current and completed loan status.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

BorrowerRate and Credit score range (Upper) have a positive correlation with credit grade. The safer the loan, the lower the borrower rate and the higher the credit score range (upper). Loans with a 12 or 36 month term have identical first and third quartiles.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Open Revolving accounts and monthly payments have a strong positive correlation.

It seems that there is some positive correlation when plotting CreditScoreRangeLower and OpenRevolvingAccounts (Middle left graph)

In [ ]:
loan_variables1 = ['CurrentDelinquencies', 'BorrowerAPR', 'CreditScoreRangeUpper']
sb.heatmap(loans[loan_variables1].corr(), cmap='summer',annot= True, vmin= 0);

BorrowerAPR and CurrentDelinquencies show a slight positive correlation of 0.15. BorrowerAPR and CreditScoreRangeUpper have the most negative correlation with -0.43, which is surprising.

In [ ]:
loan_variables2 = ['CreditGrade', 'BorrowerAPR', 'CurrentDelinquencies']
i = sb.FacetGrid(data = loans, col='CreditGrade', col_order= creditgrade_order, )
i.map(plt.scatter, 'BorrowerAPR', 'CurrentDelinquencies', alpha= 0.5)
i.fig.suptitle('BorrowerAPR and Current Delinquencies in each Credit Grade')
i.fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.8);

As the credit grade lowers, the number of loans with a high amount of current delinquencies increases.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Seeing loans with a risker grade have more current delinquencies and BorrowerAPR helped reinforce my feature of interest.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I was surprised that there was a negative correlation between BorrowerAPR and CreditScoreRangeUpper.
